    <h2>The RIPper</h2>

    <p>Please direct all queries and suggestions to: <a href="mailto:theripper.fungi@gmail.com">theripper.fungi@gmail.com</a></p>
    <p>
        The RIPper is a set of web-based tools designed for analyses of Repeat-Induced Point (RIP)
        mutations in genome sequences of Ascomycota. The RIP pathway is a fungal
        genome defense mechanism that is aimed at identifying repeated and duplicated motifs into
        which cytosine to thymine transition mutations are introduced. RIP serves to deactivate and
        counteract the deleterious consequences of selfish or mobile DNA elements in fungal
        genomes. The occurrence, genetic context and frequency of RIP mutations are widely used
        to assess the activity of this pathway in genomic regions of interest. The RIPper is, therefore,
        specifically geared to automate the investigation of changes in RIP product and substrate
        frequencies in fungal lineages.
    </p>
    <p>
        This bioinformatic tool generates genome-wide RIP data that
        is summarized in a RIP profile for each genome sequence investigated. The RIPper is further
        useful for investigating and visualizing changes in RIP mutations across the length of the
        sequence of interest, allowing for fine-scale RIP analysis. The RIPper effectively identifies
        large consecutively RIP affected genomic regions and provides RIP statistics for an entire
        genome assembly. The RIPPer can also calculate the total proportion
        of a genome assembly altered by RIP.
    </p>
    <h2>What is RIP?</h2>
    <p>
        RIP is a genome defence mechanism unique to fungi. Unlike other
        genome defence mechanisms, RIP permanently mutates targeted regions by inducing
        cytosine to thymine biased transition mutations. RIP targets duplicated gene regions and
        repeated sequences such as Transposable Element (TE) sequences.
    </p>
    <h2>Large RIP Affected Regions (LRARs)</h2>
    <p>
        LRARs play an important role in fungal genome evolution. In RIP-capable
        fungi, the genomic regions that are RIP affected often span thousands of base pairs
        and constitute a considerable proportion of the genomes. Regions that are extensively targeted by RIP are
        typically characterized by reduced GC content, reduced coding capacity and have
        overall high composite and product RIP index values are usually high. For instance, the genome of the
        pathogenic fungus <i>Leptospaeria maculans</i> is  segmented into AT-rich and
        GC equilibrated genomic compartments due to RIP activity (Rouxel <i>et al.</i>, 2011). RIP
        also facilitates sequence diversification in the targeted regions and actively contributes to
        evolution of the dispensable genomic compartments (Rouxel <i>et al.</i> 2011, Meerupati <i>et al.</i>
        2013).
    </p>

    <p>
        The RIPPer can identify LRARs.
        The criteria for LRARs can be adjusted according to user preferences. Standard parameters
        for identifying LRARs using The RIPper is seven consecutive windows (4 000 bp)
        displaying RIP activity based on RIP product, substrate and composite index values. An
        index chain describes the total count of windows needed to be consecutively RIP affected to
        define a LRAR. For more stringent analysis, the minimum composite index value considered
        for each window can be adjusted. The data generated using the ‘Calculate LRAR’ tool
        provides information on the genomic location, the total count of consecutive RIP affected
        windows, average RIP index values across the length of the LRAR and the average GC
        content of each LRAR identified
    </p>

