    <h2>Background on measuring RIP mutations</h2>
    <p>
        The RIPper measures changes in RIP mutations based on the principles proposed by
        Margolin <i>et al.</i> 1998, Lewis <i>et al.</i> 2009 and Selker <i>et al.</i> 2003.
    </p>

    <h2>
        RIP substrate index
    </h2>
    <p>
        Calculates the index values in sequences that have not been RIP affected <br />
        <i>Substrate Index Value</i> [CpA +TpG/ ApC + GpT]: 0.9 ≥ x <br />
        values less than 0.9 are RIP affected. Margolin <i>et al.</i> 1998 and Sekker <i>et al.</i> 2003
    </p>

    <h2>RIP product index</h2>
    <p>
        An increase in RIP products indicate that RIP mutations have occurred <br />
        <i>Product Index Value</i> [TpA/ ApT]: 0.8 ≤ x ≥ 1.1 <br />
        Values greater than 1.1 indicates that the genomic region is RIP affected. Values below 0.8 indicate <br />
        that a region is not RIP affected. Margolin <i>et al.</i> 1998 and Sekker <i>et al.</i> 2003
    </p>

    <h2>RIP composite index</h2>
    <p>
        Changes in both RIP substrate and RIP product index values are considered in calculating the <br />
        RIP composite index values in a genomic region <br />
        <i>Composite Index Value</i> [(TpA/ ApT) – (CpA + TpG/ ApC + GpT)]: x ≥ 0 <br />
        Therefore, a positive RIP composite index value implies that the region is RIP affected. <br />
        Lewis <i>et al.</i> 2009
    </p>

